## Explicit ECS Review (Deep Dive)

### ECS Finding A1: Query/read APIs mutate world state on missing components
Evidence: `World::HasComponent`, `World::GetComponent`, and `World::RemoveComponent` route through `GetOrCreateStore<T>()`, which inserts a store when absent.
Risk: read paths unexpectedly allocate/modify ECS state; hidden memory growth and harder debugging.
Best-practice direction: split read-only lookup from creation (`FindStore<T>() const` + `TryGetComponent<T>()`) so reads never mutate.
Priority: High

### ECS Finding A2: `View<...>()` allocates every call
Evidence: `World::View` builds and returns a fresh `std::vector<Entity>` each invocation.
Risk: per-frame heap churn in every system update/render pass; frame-time instability as entity counts grow.
Best-practice direction: return a lightweight iterable view/iterator pair over an anchor store with inline component checks and zero dynamic allocation.
Priority: High

### ECS Finding A3: Component storage is hash-map based (not data-oriented)
Evidence: `ComponentStore<T>` stores components in `std::unordered_map<Entity, T>`.
Risk: poor cache locality and pointer chasing during hot loops; ECS loses its core performance advantage at medium/high entity counts.
Best-practice direction: move hot components to sparse-set + dense array layout (`sparse[entity] -> denseIndex`, contiguous `denseComponents`).
Priority: High

### ECS Finding A4: Entity identity has no generation/version
Evidence: `Entity` is a raw incrementing `u32` with no alive/version check in `World`.
Risk: stale handles are indistinguishable from valid entities after lifecycle changes; bugs become silent data corruption instead of safe failure.
Best-practice direction: use `(index, generation)` entities and validate on every access.
Priority: Medium-High

### ECS Finding A5: Structural mutations are immediate (no ECS command buffer)
Evidence: systems can add/remove components directly through `World` API while other systems may be iterating stores in the same frame.
Risk: iterator invalidation/order-dependent behavior as feature complexity increases.
Best-practice direction: stage structural changes in a command buffer and flush at deterministic sync points (end of simulation tick).
Priority: Medium-High

## Best-Possible ECS Target Design

1. Entity model: 64-bit entity handle (`index + generation`) with central alive table and recycle list.
2. Storage model: sparse-set dense storage per component for cache-friendly iteration; hash maps reserved for low-frequency/editor-only data.
3. Query model: compile-time typed views (`View<A,B,...>`) that are non-allocating and iterate the smallest anchor set.
4. Mutation model: command buffer for `Create/Destroy/Add/Remove`, applied between system phases.
5. Scheduling model: explicit phases (`Input`, `Sim`, `PostSim`, `RenderPrep`, `Render`) with declared read/write component access.
6. Singleton model: explicit singleton registry (`SetSingleton<T>`, `TryGetSingleton<T>`) instead of first-match iteration conventions.
7. Render boundary: render systems read an immutable `RenderContext` prepared once per frame (camera, viewport, debug flags), not ad-hoc ECS scans.

## Migration Path (Pragmatic)

1. Introduce non-mutating component reads (`TryGetComponent`, `HasComponent` via `FindStore`) and keep current stores.
2. Replace `View` vector return with iterable range object (no allocations), then migrate all systems.
3. Add entity generation/version validation without changing external gameplay code.
4. Add command buffer for structural mutations and flush in `World::UpdateSystems` boundary.
5. Convert hottest components (`Transform`, `Velocity`/movement intent, `Sprite`) to dense storage first; keep fallback map-store adapter for others.
6. Add singleton APIs for camera/player and remove `first + break` logic from systems.

## Priority Order (Suggested)
1. Make ECS reads non-mutating and replace allocating `View` with zero-allocation iterables (High).
2. Reduce `Game` service-locator coupling via explicit services interface/dependency injection (High).
3. Move hot ECS component stores to dense/sparse-set layout (High).
4. Add entity generation/version validation for safer lifecycle handling (Medium-High).
5. Add ECS command-buffered structural mutations for deterministic updates (Medium-High).
6. Add debug overlay stride/LOD toggle for very large tilemaps (Medium).

